  "prompt": "Can the sun melt snow in below freezing temperatures?",
  "response": "Yes, the sun can melt snow even in below freezing temperatures. This phenomenon occurs because sunlight can directly heat the snow, particularly if the snow surface is darkened by impurities or if there is direct absorption of solar radiation. Additionally, the sun's energy can warm objects (like rocks or pavement) which can then radiate heat and contribute to melting the snow around them. Furthermore, the air may feel colder than the surface temperature in direct sunlight, allowing daytime heating to cause melting even when ambient temperatures are below freezing.",
